Honorable senators, what happened last Tuesday?
A Selection Committee was formed.
I attended the first meeting of this committee yesterday.
And I expected the committee to admit that he did not know what to do with the independent senators.
Which does not concern me so much for now.
The members of the Selection Committee may have some impact.
On the work that a senator will undertake over the next two years.
It is an important committee, since in principle these nine senators determine which committee will sit on certain senators.
I went to committee yesterday to find out that one of the nine senators was absent.
He had sent a replacement.
Honorable senators, I will not name anyone.
You see how nice I am, is not it?
Senators will have to do their own research to find out who was at fault.
When a person accepts a job, it must accomplish it.
The women who sit on the Senate have proved.
They fulfilled their duty much better than the majority of men in the Senate.
I remember the meetings of the subcommittee on veterans in February 1998.
Neither the Senate nor the House of Commons sat at that time.
Three Liberal senators attended the committee's deliberations, all of them women.
The leaders of the Senate could not find a man to sit on this committee.
I could quote, word for word, what the Honorable Senator Carstairs answered the question I asked him.
I asked him: "What were the criteria applied? "
She said that she was the first to address the issue of women's representation in a report.
Which she drafted on parliamentary associations in 1993.
The delegations at that time were made up entirely of men.
In this regard, I would like to remind you that I was replaced by Senator Finestone for a few years.
However, I am still waiting for an opportunity to re-join my favorite association.
